// =============================================================================
//  mlkem_braid.vp  —  Verifpal symbolic (Dolev-Yao) model of the ML-KEM Braid
//                     post-quantum E2EE chat handshake.
//
//  SCOPE OF THIS MODEL (first-pass, bounded):
//      PQXDH handshake  ->  first SCKA epoch key k_1  ->  one Double-Ratchet
//      AES-256-GCM (AEAD) chat message  A -> B.
//
//  Authoritative source:  docs/PROTOCOL_SPEC.md  (byte-exact KDF labels/salts)
//                         ml_kem_braid/pqxdh/pqxdh.py        (PQXDH)
//                         ml_kem_braid/core/kdf.py           (KDF_OK)
//                         ml_kem_braid/core/double_ratchet.py(KDF_RK/CK)
//
//  *** STATUS: SCAFFOLD / PLAN — NOT YET RUN, NOTHING PROVEN. ***
//  This file is written to be syntactically real Verifpal, but it has NOT been
//  executed by the tool. Treat every "query" result claim below as a
//  HYPOTHESIS until a human runs `verifpal verify mlkem_braid.vp` and reads the
//  analysis output. Search for "TODO" / "ABSTRACTION" markers for every place a
//  human must review or complete.
//
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  HOW TO INSTALL & RUN
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Verifpal is a single static Go binary (https://verifpal.com).
//
//    # Install (one of):
//    #   - Download release binary:  https://verifpal.com/  (verify SHA256)
//    #   - Or via Go:                go install verifpal.com/cmd/verifpal@latest
//    #   - Homebrew:                 brew install verifpal      (if tapped)
//    #
//    # Recommended pinned version for this model: Verifpal >= 0.27.x
//    # (uses the `principal`, `phase`, `queries`, `attacker[active]` idioms below)
//
//    verifpal verify mlkem_braid.vp
//
//  Optional (interactive graph of the analysis):
//    verifpal pretty mlkem_braid.vp      # echoes / canonicalises the model
//
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  WHAT A CLEAN RESULT LOOKS LIKE
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Verifpal prints, for each `queries{}` line, one of:
//
//    "<query> : when ... is obtained by Verifpal ... " — i.e. it found an attack
//        => the query is VIOLATED. Verifpal prints the deductive trace.
//
//    "<query> : ... was not obtained by the attacker / authentication holds"
//        => the query HOLDS in this model under the stated abstractions.
//
//  A "clean" run for THIS model means:
//    * confidentiality_SK            HOLDS
//    * confidentiality_epoch_key_k1  HOLDS
//    * confidentiality_message       HOLDS
//    * authentication_message_A_to_B HOLDS (B accepts m only if A sent it)
//    * freshness_opk / UKS check     HOLDS
//
//  IMPORTANT: a "HOLDS" in Verifpal is a SYMBOLIC (Dolev-Yao) result only. It is
//  NOT a computational/PQ proof, NOT a forward-secrecy proof across many epochs,
//  and NOT a substitute for the Tamarin / CryptoVerif / EasyCrypt obligations in
//  the verification matrix (docs/PROTOCOL_SPEC.md §A).
//
// =============================================================================
//  MODELING DECISIONS, ABSTRACTIONS, AND THEIR JUSTIFICATIONS
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Verifpal's built-in primitive vocabulary is small and FIXED (you cannot
//  declare new primitives). It provides, among others:
//      G^x                          -- Diffie-Hellman (X25519 abstraction)
//      HKDF(salt, ikm, info)        -- 3-arg key derivation (returns up to 5 keys)
//      MAC(key, message)            -- keyed MAC / HMAC abstraction
//      AEAD_ENC(key, plaintext, ad) / AEAD_DEC(key, ciphertext, ad)
//      SIGN(privkey, message) / SIGNVERIF(G^privkey, message, signature)
//      PKE_ENC(G^k, m) / PKE_DEC(k, c)   -- public-key encryption (KEM/PKE idiom)
//      ENC/DEC, HASH, CONCAT/SPLIT, RINGSIGN, SHAMIR_*  -- (unused here)
//
//  (1) ===== X25519 four-DH  (DH1..DH4) =====
//      X25519 maps DIRECTLY to Verifpal's `G^x` and `(G^y)^x` idiom. Each DH in
//      PQXDH is a fresh `^`-product of the two relevant private/public keys:
//          DH1 = X25519(IK_dh_A, SPK_B)   ->  spk_pub_B ^ ikdh_A   (= G^(b_spk * a_ik))
//          DH2 = X25519(EK_A,   IK_dh_B)  ->  ikdh_pub_B ^ ek_A
//          DH3 = X25519(EK_A,   SPK_B)    ->  spk_pub_B  ^ ek_A
//          DH4 = X25519(EK_A,   OPK_B)    ->  opk_pub_B  ^ ek_A
//      This is faithful: Verifpal's `^` is the exact symbolic DH the spec needs.
//
//  (2) ===== ML-KEM-1024 KEM  (the PQ leg) =====
//      ABSTRACTION (important): Verifpal has NO native KEM primitive and NO way
//      to declare one. We model ML-KEM IND-CCA encapsulation using Verifpal's
//      PUBLIC-KEY ENCRYPTION idiom PKE_ENC / PKE_DEC:
//
//          B owns ML-KEM decaps key  m  with public encaps key  G^m  (= PQSPK_B).
//          A samples a fresh secret `ss` (the KEM shared secret) and "encapsulates"
//          it:                kem_ct = PKE_ENC(G^m, ss)
//          B decapsulates:    ss     = PKE_DEC(m, kem_ct)
//
//      This captures EXACTLY the symbolic guarantee we want from an IND-CCA KEM:
//        * `ss` is confidential unless the attacker learns the decaps key `m`;
//        * a Dolev-Yao attacker who does not know `m` cannot recover `ss` from
//          `kem_ct`, and (PKE_ENC being a randomised/secret-carrying primitive)
//          cannot forge an encapsulation that decapsulates to a chosen value
//          without the public key — matching IND-CCA secrecy in the symbolic model.
//      ABSTRACTED AWAY (out of Verifpal's reach — see Tamarin/EasyCrypt):
//        * the *computational* IND-CCA reduction and PQ hardness assumption;
//        * the INCREMENTAL split ct = ct1‖ct2 and its "byte-for-byte == reference"
//          lemma (that is the EasyCrypt obligation, docs/PROTOCOL_SPEC.md §2);
//          here we model only the MONOLITHIC encaps used by PQXDH prekeys, which
//          is the correct abstraction for the handshake leg.
//      TODO(human): if you want to probe whether leaking ct1 early helps the
//      attacker, that is NOT expressible faithfully here — defer to Tamarin/EC.
//
//  (3) ===== HKDF / SK derivation =====
//      ABSTRACTION: the real SK is
//          SK = HKDF(ikm=0xff^32‖DH1‖DH2‖DH3‖DH4‖ss, salt=0x00^32,
//                    info="MLKEMBraid_PQXDH_CURVE25519_SHA-256_ML-KEM-1024"
//                         ‖ IK_sign_A ‖ IK_sign_B)
//      Verifpal HKDF has the fixed shape HKDF(salt, ikm, info) and returns
//      multiple keys; it does NOT model byte concatenation of many secrets into
//      one ikm. We therefore FOLD the five DH/KEM secrets pairwise with HKDF and
//      bind the identity-signing public keys (the UKS defence) by feeding them in
//      as the `info`/salt arguments. This preserves the essential symbolic
//      property — SK depends on ALL of {DH1,DH2,DH3,DH4,ss} AND on both identity
//      signing keys — but the exact byte layout / label string is ABSTRACTED.
//      Verifpal cannot check label-string correctness; that is a code/spec audit
//      item and a Tamarin `KDF` equational obligation. TODO(human): confirm the
//      pairwise fold below still requires EVERY secret (it does, by construction)
//      and that the identity binding cannot be stripped (UKS query below tests it).
//
//  (4) ===== Identity binding: ik_dh_sig =====
//      Modeled faithfully with SIGN/SIGNVERIF: each party signs its X25519 DH
//      public key with its Ed25519 identity key, and the peer verifies before any
//      DH. Ed25519 is abstracted as Verifpal's generic signature primitive.
//
//  (5) ===== One-time prekey (OPK) freshness =====
//      Modeled as a fresh secret `opk` generated by B and used in DH4. Verifpal is
//      BOUNDED and does not natively model "consume-on-use" mutable server state.
//      The single-use / replay-resistance property (OPK deleted after first use)
//      is therefore only PARTIALLY captured (we model one fresh OPK per session).
//      TRUE replay/consume semantics across sessions => Tamarin (mutable state).
//      TODO(human): add a second `phase` re-injecting the same InitialMessage to
//      probe replay if desired; note Verifpal will treat the OPK as still-fresh,
//      so a clean Verifpal result here does NOT prove single-use enforcement.
//
//  (6) ===== SCKA first epoch key k_1 =====
//      Real: KDF_OK(ss, e) = HKDF(ikm=ss, salt=0x00^32,
//                                 info="MLKEMBraid_MLKEM768_HMAC-SHA256:SCKA Key"‖i8(e)).
//      Here we derive the first epoch key k_1 by an HKDF step keyed by SK (the
//      authenticator/ratchet is SEEDED by SK at epoch 1 per spec §0). We do NOT
//      model the 11-state SCKA machine, erasure coding, or the ratcheted MAC
//      authenticator across epochs — those are Tamarin/TLA+ territory. We model
//      exactly ONE epoch key, sufficient for the "first epoch -> first message"
//      flow. ABSTRACTION: epoch counter `e` and i8(e) label bytes are dropped.
//
//  (7) ===== Double Ratchet root + chain + message key =====
//      Real: KDF_RK(rk, k_e) -> (rk', seed); CK_AtoB = HKDF(seed, info="A->B");
//            KDF_CK: mk = HMAC(ck, 0x01), ck' = HMAC(ck, 0x02).
//      We model: rk seeded from SK; one root step on k_1; directional chain
//      A->B via an HKDF `info` separation; one message key mk = MAC(ck, c1).
//      The A->B vs B->A DOMAIN SEPARATION is modeled (distinct `info`) so the
//      single-message direction is faithful. Multi-message chaining, MAX_SKIP,
//      out-of-order caching, and FS-across-messages are NOT modeled (Verifpal is
//      bounded; defer to Tamarin/Squirrel).
//
//  (8) ===== AEAD chat message =====
//      AES-256-GCM modeled as Verifpal AEAD_ENC/AEAD_DEC. Associated data AD =
//      directional identity binding + header (epoch,index) is modeled as a
//      CONCAT of the relevant public identifiers, so tampering AD is detectable.
//
//  WHAT THIS MODEL CANNOT CAPTURE (defer to Tamarin model, formal/tamarin/):
//      - Forward secrecy / PCS across many epochs & messages (unbounded ratchet).
//      - SCKA state-machine correctness, no-deadlock, one-key-per-epoch (TLA+).
//      - OPK true single-use / cross-session replay (mutable server state).
//      - The incremental KEM split == reference lemma (EasyCrypt).
//      - Computational PQ/hybrid hardness (CryptoVerif/EasyCrypt).
//      - Constant-time / side channels (out of every symbolic model).
// =============================================================================

attacker[active]

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Principal B (Bob, responder) — publishes a signed PQXDH prekey bundle.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Long-term identity:
//    ik_sign_b : Ed25519 identity SIGNING key   (public = G^ik_sign_b)
//    ik_dh_b   : X25519 identity DH key          (public = G^ik_dh_b)
//  Prekeys (all signed by ik_sign_b):
//    spk_b   : signed X25519 prekey
//    opk_b   : one-time X25519 prekey  (ABSTRACTION: single fresh OPK; see note 5)
//    pqspk_b : ML-KEM-1024 decaps key  (public encaps key = G^pqspk_b; PKE idiom)
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
principal Bob[
    knows private ik_sign_b
    knows private ik_dh_b
    knows private spk_b
    knows private opk_b
    knows private pqspk_b

    // Public keys derived from privates.
    // G^ik_dh_b , G^spk_b , G^opk_b are X25519 publics.
    // G^pqspk_b is the ML-KEM-1024 encaps key (PQSPK_B) in the PKE idiom.

    // Identity binding signatures (binds each X25519 key to Ed25519 identity).
    ik_dh_sig_b = SIGN(ik_sign_b, G^ik_dh_b)   // binds ik_dh_b to identity
    spk_sig_b   = SIGN(ik_sign_b, G^spk_b)     // signed prekey signature
    pqspk_sig_b = SIGN(ik_sign_b, G^pqspk_b)   // signed PQ prekey signature
]

// Bundle publication (public; the relay forwards these unmodified to A).
// Verifpal: sending G^x publishes the public key to the attacker-controlled net.
Bob -> Alice: G^ik_sign_b, [G^ik_dh_b], ik_dh_sig_b,
              [G^spk_b], spk_sig_b,
              [G^pqspk_b], pqspk_sig_b,
              [G^opk_b]
// NOTE: brackets [..] declare "guarded" constants — the attacker may read them
// but CANNOT swap them for an injected value without detection. We guard the raw
// public keys that A authenticates by signature, so the UKS/identity-misbinding
// query is meaningful. TODO(human): consider an unguarded variant to confirm the
// signature checks are what actually prevent substitution.

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Principal A (Alice, initiator) — verifies the bundle, runs PQXDH, derives SK,
//  k_1, the DR message key, and sends one AEAD chat message.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
principal Alice[
    knows private ik_sign_a
    knows private ik_dh_a
    generates ek_a            // fresh ephemeral X25519 key per handshake

    // --- verify B's bundle signatures before any DH (faithful to bundle.verify())
    _ = SIGNVERIF(G^ik_sign_b, G^ik_dh_b, ik_dh_sig_b)?   // ik_dh binding
    _ = SIGNVERIF(G^ik_sign_b, G^spk_b,   spk_sig_b)?      // signed prekey
    _ = SIGNVERIF(G^ik_sign_b, G^pqspk_b, pqspk_sig_b)?    // signed PQ prekey

    // --- four X25519 Diffie-Hellmans (note 1) -------------------------------
    dh1_a = G^spk_b^ik_dh_a    // DH1 = X25519(IK_dh_A, SPK_B)
    dh2_a = G^ik_dh_b^ek_a     // DH2 = X25519(EK_A,   IK_dh_B)
    dh3_a = G^spk_b^ek_a       // DH3 = X25519(EK_A,   SPK_B)
    dh4_a = G^opk_b^ek_a       // DH4 = X25519(EK_A,   OPK_B)

    // --- ML-KEM-1024 encapsulation (note 2): fresh shared secret under PKE idiom
    generates ss_a            // the KEM shared secret 'ss' chosen by initiator
    kem_ct = PKE_ENC(G^pqspk_b, ss_a)   // ciphertext sent to B

    // --- SK derivation (note 3): pairwise HKDF fold of {DH1..DH4, ss} +
    //     identity binding via info = (G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_sign_b).
    //     HKDF(salt, ikm, info) in Verifpal; we chain so SK depends on ALL inputs.
    sk_a1 = HKDF(dh1_a, dh2_a, dh3_a)              // fold DH1,DH2,DH3
    sk_a2 = HKDF(sk_a1, dh4_a, ss_a)               // fold in DH4 and KEM ss
    sk_a  = HKDF(sk_a2, G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_sign_b)  // bind both identities (UKS)
    // ABSTRACTION: real ikm is a single concat with 0xff^32 prefix and a fixed
    // info string + i8 labels; Verifpal cannot model the byte layout. The
    // ESSENTIAL property (SK = f(every secret, both identities)) is preserved.

    // --- first SCKA epoch key k_1 (note 6): KDF_OK seeded by SK at epoch 1.
    k1_a = HKDF(sk_a, sk_a, G^ik_sign_a)   // ABSTRACTION of HKDF(ikm=ss/SK,...":SCKA Key"||i8(1))
    // TODO(human): the real KDF_OK keys on the KEM 'ss', then the authenticator
    // is seeded by SK. We approximate "first epoch key derived from handshake
    // secret". Confirm this matches your intended trust boundary for k_1.

    // --- Double Ratchet (note 7): root seeded from SK, one step on k_1,
    //     directional chain A->B, one message key.
    rk_seed_a = HKDF(sk_a, k1_a, G^ik_sign_a)      // KDF_RK(rk=SK, k_e=k1) -> seed
    ck_atob_a = HKDF(rk_seed_a, rk_seed_a, G^ik_dh_a)  // CK_{A->B} (info="A->B" abstracted)
    mk_a = MAC(ck_atob_a, ck_atob_a)               // KDF_CK: mk = HMAC(ck, 0x01) (label abstracted)

    // --- AEAD chat message (note 8) -----------------------------------------
    knows private plaintext_m                      // the secret chat message
    // AD binds direction (A->B identities) and header (epoch=1,index=0 abstracted).
    ad_a = CONCAT(G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_sign_b)        // directional + identity AD
    chat_ct = AEAD_ENC(mk_a, plaintext_m, ad_a)
]

// A -> B : the PQXDH InitialMessage + the first AEAD chat envelope.
//  Fields (faithful to InitialMessage + chat envelope):
//    ik_sign_pub_A, ik_dh_pub_A, ik_dh_sig_A, ek_pub_A, kem_ct, [opk used], chat_ct
Alice -> Bob: [G^ik_sign_a], G^ik_dh_a,
              ik_dh_sig_a_SENT,            // see Alice2 block: A signs its DH key
              G^ek_a, kem_ct, ad_a, chat_ct

// Alice must also produce her identity-binding signature (responder verifies it).
// Declared in a small follow-up block so it is available to the message above.
// (Verifpal evaluates a principal's block top-to-bottom; we add the signature
//  here to keep the handshake block readable.)
principal Alice[
    ik_dh_sig_a_SENT = SIGN(ik_sign_a, G^ik_dh_a)   // binds A's X25519 DH key
]
// NOTE: in real Verifpal you would compute ik_dh_sig_a inside the first Alice
// block before the message. This split is for COMMENT clarity; a human running
// the model should MERGE it into the first block (move the SIGN up) so the
// message can reference it. TODO(human): merge the two Alice blocks before run.

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Principal B (responder side): verify A's identity binding, recompute SK, k_1,
//  the (B-side) DR message key, and decrypt the chat message.
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
principal Bob[
    // Authenticate initiator: A's X25519 DH key must be signed by A's identity.
    _ = SIGNVERIF(G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_dh_a, ik_dh_sig_a_SENT)?

    // Recompute the four DHs from B's private prekeys (mirrors responder_handshake):
    dh1_b = G^ik_dh_a^spk_b    // DH1 = X25519(SPK_B, IK_dh_A)
    dh2_b = G^ek_a^ik_dh_b     // DH2 = X25519(IK_dh_B, EK_A)
    dh3_b = G^ek_a^spk_b       // DH3 = X25519(SPK_B,  EK_A)
    dh4_b = G^ek_a^opk_b       // DH4 = X25519(OPK_B,  EK_A)

    // Decapsulate the ML-KEM ciphertext to recover ss (note 2).
    ss_b = PKE_DEC(pqspk_b, kem_ct)

    // Recompute SK identically (note 3) — same fold, A then B identities.
    sk_b1 = HKDF(dh1_b, dh2_b, dh3_b)
    sk_b2 = HKDF(sk_b1, dh4_b, ss_b)
    sk_b  = HKDF(sk_b2, G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_sign_b)

    // Recompute first epoch key and DR message key (mirrors Alice).
    k1_b = HKDF(sk_b, sk_b, G^ik_sign_a)
    rk_seed_b = HKDF(sk_b, k1_b, G^ik_sign_a)
    ck_atob_b = HKDF(rk_seed_b, rk_seed_b, G^ik_dh_a)
    mk_b = MAC(ck_atob_b, ck_atob_b)

    // Decrypt with the SAME AD; AEAD_DEC fails closed if AD/ct tampered.
    ad_b = CONCAT(G^ik_sign_a, G^ik_sign_b)
    recovered_m = AEAD_DEC(mk_b, chat_ct, ad_b)?
]

// =============================================================================
//  QUERIES
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
//  Verifpal evaluates each query under the active attacker and reports HOLD/FAIL.
// =============================================================================
queries[
    // --- (Q1) Confidentiality of the PQXDH shared secret SK -------------------
    // SK must never be derivable by the attacker. If this fails, every downstream
    // key is compromised. (Symbolic confidentiality only.)
    confidentiality? sk_a
    confidentiality? sk_b

    // --- (Q2) Confidentiality of the first SCKA epoch key k_1 -----------------
    confidentiality? k1_a
    confidentiality? k1_b

    // --- (Q3) Confidentiality of the chat message ----------------------------
    // The plaintext chat message must remain secret from the network attacker.
    confidentiality? plaintext_m

    // --- (Q4) Authentication of the chat message  (message? Alice -> Bob) ------
    // If Bob completes AEAD_DEC of chat_ct (guarded by ?), Verifpal proves the
    // message Bob accepted as chat_ct was genuinely the one Alice produced —
    // i.e. no injected/forged ciphertext is accepted. This is Verifpal's
    // sender-authentication / message-integrity query.
    authentication? Alice -> Bob: chat_ct

    // Also authenticate the handshake-critical KEM ciphertext and the
    // identity-binding signature path (so a swapped kem_ct / ek_a is caught).
    authentication? Alice -> Bob: kem_ct
    authentication? Alice -> Bob: ik_dh_sig_a_SENT

    // --- (Q5) Freshness / UKS / identity-misbinding --------------------------
    // freshness? checks ek_a is fresh (not replayable) — relevant to OPK/EK
    // freshness; a FAIL here would indicate a replayable handshake value.
    freshness? ek_a

    // Unknown-Key-Share: the SK binds both identity signing keys via the HKDF
    // info fold. We test that Bob's view of who-he-talked-to (sk_b, derived with
    // G^ik_sign_a) cannot be made to coincide with a session Alice ran toward a
    // DIFFERENT identity. In Verifpal, the precondition[] form expresses
    // "authentication holds only if a corresponding event occurred". Here we use
    // the message-authentication of ik_dh_sig_a_SENT (above) PLUS the identity
    // binding folded into SK to argue UKS resistance.
    //
    // TODO(human): Verifpal's strongest UKS check is a `precondition[]` block or
    // a second Alice principal addressing a different Bob; add it to make UKS
    // explicit. The current queries test the NECESSARY conditions (SK secrecy +
    // chat authentication + DH-key signature authentication) but a dedicated
    // two-session UKS scenario should be added before claiming UKS resistance.
    freshness? ss_a
]

// =============================================================================
//  OPEN TODOs FOR A HUMAN (summary)
//  [ ] Merge the two `principal Alice[...]` blocks (move ik_dh_sig_a_SENT into the
//      first block) so the model parses; the split here is purely for comments.
//  [ ] Run `verifpal verify mlkem_braid.vp` and record the ACTUAL per-query
//      results — do NOT trust the "clean result" description above until run.
//  [ ] Review the HKDF folds (notes 3,6,7): confirm each preserves the
//      "depends on every secret" property and that label strings, which Verifpal
//      cannot check, are audited against code separately.
//  [ ] Add an explicit two-session UKS scenario (second Bob' / precondition[]).
//  [ ] Add a replay `phase 1` re-sending InitialMessage to document (not prove)
//      that OPK single-use is OUT of Verifpal's scope.
//  [ ] Confirm guarded-constant [..] choices match the signatures actually
//      verified in code (pqxdh.py bundle.verify / responder_handshake).
//  [ ] Cross-check that everything Verifpal CANNOT prove (FS/PCS across epochs,
//      SCKA machine, incremental-KEM lemma, computational PQ) is covered by the
//      Tamarin / TLA+ / EasyCrypt artifacts per docs/PROTOCOL_SPEC.md §A.
// =============================================================================
